1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:01,891
Welcome back!

2
00:00:01,891 --> 00:00:08,128
Today we're revising two systems that work as a team: the respiratory system and the circul

3
00:00:08,128 --> 00:00:09,019
atory system.

4
00:00:09,019 --> 00:00:14,846
We'll follow oxygen all the way from the air you breathe to the muscles in your legs,

5
00:00:14,846 --> 00:00:17,930
and learn the exact phrases that score marks.

6
00:00:18,930 --> 00:00:21,102
First, what each system is for.

7
00:00:21,102 --> 00:00:27,125
The respiratory system lets us breathe: it takes in oxygen and removes carbon dioxide.

8
00:00:27,125 --> 00:00:33,008
The circulatory system transports oxygen and digested food to all parts of the body,

9
00:00:33,008 --> 00:00:36,370
and carries wastes away. Now, an important trap.

10
00:00:36,370 --> 00:00:41,273
Breathing means taking air in and pushing air out — a physical action.

11
00:00:41,273 --> 00:00:47,366
Respiration means releasing energy from digested food, using oxygen, inside every cell.

12
00:00:47,366 --> 00:00:52,830
They are not the same! We breathe to supply the oxygen needed for respiration.

13
00:00:53,830 --> 00:00:58,243
Let's follow the path air takes: nose, then windpipe, then lungs,

14
00:00:58,243 --> 00:00:59,940
and finally the air sacs.

15
00:00:59,940 --> 00:01:03,267
At the nose, hairs and mucus trap dust and germs,

16
00:01:03,267 --> 00:01:06,323
and the nose also warms and moistens the air.

17
00:01:06,323 --> 00:01:12,094
The windpipe, or trachea, is a tube that carries air from the nose down to the lungs.

18
00:01:12,094 --> 00:01:16,440
The lungs are the two organs where gaseous exchange takes place.

19
00:01:16,440 --> 00:01:18,680
And inside them are the air sacs,

20
00:01:18,680 --> 00:01:22,687
where oxygen enters the blood and carbon dioxide leaves it.

21
00:01:23,687 --> 00:01:28,748
When we breathe in, air with more oxygen enters, and the chest expands.

22
00:01:28,748 --> 00:01:34,593
When we breathe out, air with more carbon dioxide leaves, and the chest contracts.

23
00:01:34,593 --> 00:01:39,939
Now here's a trap that catches many pupils: inhaled air is not pure oxygen,

24
00:01:39,939 --> 00:01:43,004
and exhaled air is not pure carbon dioxide.

25
00:01:43,004 --> 00:01:46,711
Inhaled air has more oxygen and less carbon dioxide.

26
00:01:46,711 --> 00:01:50,418
Exhaled air has less oxygen and more carbon dioxide.

27
00:01:50,418 --> 00:01:54,409
Both gases are always present — only the amounts change.

28
00:01:55,410 --> 00:01:59,230
Here's the key idea of the whole topic: gaseous exchange.

29
00:01:59,230 --> 00:02:04,123
Memorise this: oxygen from the air in the air sacs passes into the blood.

30
00:02:04,123 --> 00:02:09,016
At the same time, carbon dioxide from the blood passes into the air sacs,

31
00:02:09,016 --> 00:02:13,172
and is breathed out. And why are the air sacs so good at this?

32
00:02:13,172 --> 00:02:17,461
Because there are millions of them, giving a large surface area,

33
00:02:17,461 --> 00:02:20,076
so gaseous exchange can happen quickly.

34
00:02:21,076 --> 00:02:25,355
Now the circulatory system. The heart is a pump, made of muscle.

35
00:02:25,355 --> 00:02:29,233
It pumps blood to all parts of the body, without stopping.

36
00:02:29,233 --> 00:02:32,041
When the heart beats, we can feel a pulse.

37
00:02:32,041 --> 00:02:37,390
And here's the trap: the heart does not make blood, and it does not make oxygen.

38
00:02:37,390 --> 00:02:43,208
Its job is to pump the blood, so that the blood can transport oxygen and digested food.

39
00:02:44,208 --> 00:02:45,990
So what does the blood carry?

40
00:02:45,990 --> 00:02:49,924
Oxygen, picked up at the lungs, and delivered to all body parts.

41
00:02:49,924 --> 00:02:54,904
Digested food, picked up at the small intestine, and delivered to all body parts.

42
00:02:54,904 --> 00:02:57,854
And carbon dioxide, picked up at the body parts,

43
00:02:57,854 --> 00:03:00,990
and delivered back to the lungs to be breathed out.

44
00:03:00,990 --> 00:03:04,432
The blood flows through tiny tubes called blood vessels,

45
00:03:04,432 --> 00:03:09,227
which reach every part of the body, so every cell can receive oxygen and food,

46
00:03:09,227 --> 00:03:10,641
and give up its wastes.

47
00:03:11,641 --> 00:03:16,993
Now let's put the systems together — this is very important for the PSLE.

48
00:03:16,993 --> 00:03:21,686
One: we breathe in, and oxygen enters the air sacs in the lungs.

49
00:03:21,686 --> 00:03:26,012
Two: the oxygen passes into the blood, by gaseous exchange.

50
00:03:26,012 --> 00:03:30,264
Three: the heart pumps the blood, transporting the oxygen,

51
00:03:30,264 --> 00:03:35,324
and digested food from the small intestine, to all parts of the body.

52
00:03:35,324 --> 00:03:41,409
Four: the body cells use the oxygen and food to release energy. That's respiration.

53
00:03:41,409 --> 00:03:46,102
Five: this produces carbon dioxide, which passes into the blood.

54
00:03:46,102 --> 00:03:51,308
And six: the blood carries it back to the lungs, and we breathe it out.

55
00:03:52,308 --> 00:03:54,331
So why do we pant when we run?

56
00:03:54,331 --> 00:04:00,064
Because the muscles are working harder, they need more oxygen to release more energy.

57
00:04:00,064 --> 00:04:05,932
So we breathe faster and deeper, to take in more oxygen and remove more carbon dioxide.

58
00:04:05,932 --> 00:04:12,003
And the heart beats faster, to pump the oxygen-carrying blood to the muscles more quickly.

59
00:04:12,003 --> 00:04:16,927
Always link it back: more oxygen, to the muscles, to release more energy.

60
00:04:17,927 --> 00:04:24,173
Answering technique for Section B. Use these keywords: gaseous exchange. Air sacs.

61
00:04:24,173 --> 00:04:29,658
Large surface area. Oxygen passes into the blood. The heart pumps blood.

62
00:04:29,658 --> 00:04:36,438
Transports, or carries. Digested food from the small intestine. To all parts of the body.

63
00:04:36,438 --> 00:04:37,962
And, release energy.

64
00:04:37,962 --> 00:04:43,599
Then use the system-link formula: oxygen enters the blood at the air sacs.

65
00:04:43,599 --> 00:04:49,694
The heart pumps the blood, which transports the oxygen to all parts of the body,

66
00:04:49,694 --> 00:04:52,360
where it is used to release energy.

67
00:04:53,360 --> 00:04:54,824
Time to test yourself!

68
00:04:54,824 --> 00:04:59,683
Explain how oxygen in the air we breathe reaches the muscles in our legs.

69
00:04:59,683 --> 00:05:01,747
Pause the video and try. Ready?

70
00:05:01,747 --> 00:05:07,804
Here's the model answer: oxygen enters the air sacs in the lungs and passes into the blood.

71
00:05:07,804 --> 00:05:13,862
The heart pumps the blood, which transports the oxygen through the blood vessels to the mus

72
00:05:13,862 --> 00:05:14,993
cles in the legs.

73
00:05:15,993 --> 00:05:21,665
Let's recap. The respiratory system takes in oxygen and removes carbon dioxide.

74
00:05:21,665 --> 00:05:27,696
The air path is nose, windpipe, lungs, air sacs — and the nose traps dust and germs.

75
00:05:27,696 --> 00:05:33,727
Gaseous exchange happens at the air sacs: oxygen into the blood, carbon dioxide out.

76
00:05:33,727 --> 00:05:37,102
Millions of air sacs give a large surface area.

77
00:05:37,102 --> 00:05:42,702
Inhaled air has more oxygen; exhaled air has more carbon dioxide — never pure!

78
00:05:42,702 --> 00:05:47,656
The circulatory system is the heart, the blood vessels and the blood.

79
00:05:47,656 --> 00:05:50,384
The heart pumps; the blood transports.

80
00:05:50,384 --> 00:05:56,846
Blood carries oxygen from the lungs and digested food from the small intestine to all body

81
00:05:56,846 --> 00:05:57,277
parts.

82
00:05:57,277 --> 00:06:03,308
And when we exercise, the muscles need more oxygen, so we breathe faster and deeper,

83
00:06:03,308 --> 00:06:05,246
and the heart beats faster.

84
00:06:06,246 --> 00:06:11,542
You've got this! Remember: the heart pumps, and the blood transports.

85
00:06:11,542 --> 00:06:17,604
Link the systems together in your answers, and those Section B marks are yours.

86
00:06:17,604 --> 00:06:21,902
Good luck with your revision, and all the best for PSLE!
